It's time to build back our community. 
It's time to build back our power. 
It's time to build back our permanence. 
It's time to build back CRENSHAW. 

Destination Crenshaw has begun constructing the streetscapes, including the Crenshaw Wall, street furniture, and landscaping along Crenshaw Blvd.  But Destination Crenshaw has another important goal: to provide job opportunities for our local workers and contractors to work—on THIS project.

Our Board of Directors and leadership team want to increase our outreach and hiring capacity for these workers and contractors. To accomplish our goal of Building Back Crenshaw, we are bidding contracts for the remaining pocket parks to engage Black contractors whose smaller companies could not compete for the entire project’s construction contract when we first bid.

Today, we honor workers and their immense contributions to society. Los Angeles labor is strong! I want to uplift the ongoing struggles of SAG-AFTRA, WGA, and UNITE HERE as they strike, start boycotts, and hit the picket lines in the name of a fair contract.

At the heart of today's celebration, we recognize the American labor movement and the sacrifices laborers and labor activists made to achieve federal adoption and more fair conditions. 

Labor Day was conceived during two of the most tumultuous times in U.S. history: the Industrial Revolution and slavery. As it stands today, unaddressed income inequality has resulted in the development of widespread inequity at an unprecedented scale. 

Labor is essential to our City's continued growth and functions. As we celebrate today's holiday, we must remember to honor the legacy and remember the movement as we work towards a better future.

All of our people should be able to be safe on our streets at all times.  We will pursue and prevent these violent folks with everything we have.

It is with great sadness that we adjourned yesterday's Council Meeting in memory of Alyce Joe Crump. Ms. Crump was an 82-year-old devout missionary who dedicated her life to the service of others. A lifetime member of AME Church, Crump held a number of offices over the years, and most notably served as a member, consultant, and secretary of the Southern California Conference Trustee Board for 30 years.

Today, we honor and celebrate Mexican Independence Day, also known as El Grito.
 
Celebrated every year on September 16 since 1810, El Grito commemorates the day that Father Miguel Hidalgo y Costilla delivered the Cry of Dolores speech calling upon the people to revolt against the Spanish rule of Mexico.

The day is typically observed with an El Grito ceremony, mirroring the battle cry issued by Father Hidalgo.

¡Viva la Independencia Nacional! ¡Viva México!

At the heart of today's celebration, we recognize Indigenous people as the first occupants of the Americas and commemorate each of their distinct histories and cultures. Our own Council District Eight sits on the ancestral and unceded land of the Shoshonian-speaking Tongva people.

Indigenous Peoples' Day was first instituted in 1992, when several Native American activists in Berkeley, California, pushed for an alternative celebration to coincide with the 500th anniversary of the arrival of Columbus in the Americas on October 12, 1492. The day quickly grew to represent a counter-celebration held on the same day each year as the U.S. federal holiday of Columbus Day, which honors Italian explorer Christopher Columbus. 

Protests for formally adopting Indigenous Peoples' Day raged on, with a growing contingent of people rejecting the idea of celebrating Christopher Columbus. After nearly two decades of protests, Indigenous Peoples' Day officially became a federal holiday in the U.S. in 2021, after President Joe Biden signed a proclamation for the celebration’s national inclusion. 

We must understand and acknowledge our colonial history and commit to learning from and partnering with Indigenous communities to advocate for their freedoms and social justice.

I wanted to rise today to recognize SEE-LA and Summer Vernon, who’s with us today.
See-LA has operated the Crenshaw Farmers Market for years. 

A few years ago, just after the city passed the $15 an hour minimum wage, a corporate grocery distributor decided they could no longer provide groceries at Slauson and Crenshaw. Not only do we have food deserts in South LA, but we also have corporations actively creating new ones. I was so happy when our office and the neighborhood went to SEE-LA and said, “The people in this neighborhood need food. Is there any way you all can do a farmers market in this space?”

They just took a couple of days, and they came, and every Saturday for several months now at Crenshaw and Slauson, starting at about eight in the morning, we have the Crenshaw Farmers Market at Slauson and Crenshaw. 

It has been a boon to our community and SEE-LA stepped in the gap in a very material way, in a situation where, again, not only do we have food deserts, but food deserts are actively being created. Because of farmers markets and organizations like SEE-LA and folks like Summer, our community is wading through this crisis. And so thank you, and thank you for being here. And thank you to the council members who brought this to us today.

Marque su calendario para celebrar nuestro evento anual del Día de los Muertos el jueves 2 de noviembre, desde las 6 pm hasta las 10 pm. El Día de los Muertos es un momento para honrar a nuestros antepasados y compartir tradiciones antiguas y nuevas.

Mark your calendars for our annual Día de los Muertos celebration on Thursday, November 2, from 6 pm to 10 pm. Día de los Muertos is a time to honor our ancestors and share old and new traditions.

Last year’s celebration was nothing short of amazing, and this year, we aim to make it even more memorable as we continue to embrace and celebrate our shared cultural heritage. We are partnering with Councilmember Eunisses Hernandez of the First District to come together as a community on the border of the Eighth and First.

LA City celebrates Clergy Appreciation Month to solidify unity in the faith community. The importance of clergy members work in our neighborhoods cannot be overstated. In times of crisis, they offer solace, support, and unity to those who follow their respective faith, and we witness their presence as reassuring and comforting. Their actions remind us in times of crisis, our shared humanity can truly transcend differences. 

I was honored to lead the Clergy Appreciation Month presentation, where each member, along with the City Attorney and City Controller, recognized a religious leader in their district. Representing the Eighth District was Dr. Mary Minor of Brookins-Kirkland Community AME Church. Dr Minor has a deep belief in the open doors of her congregation and is a pillar in our community.

It was an honor to recognize Sergeant George Graham this week at Council for our Veteran’s Day presentation.

After being drafted in 1969, Sergeant Graham joined the Air Force where he was trained as a Command and Control Specialist Technician. He was deployed to the City of Tainan in Taiwan where he was later promoted to the rank of Sergeant.

Sergeant Graham’s squadron went into temporary duty in Vietnam, and he led the troop through the perils of war.

Thank you to all our Veterans who put their lives on the line for this country!

It was a great honor to celebrate the 90th birthday of the Honorable Diane E. Watson yesterday with my colleagues at Council. 

As the first African American woman to be elected to the California State Senate and a member of the U.S. Congress, Ms. Watson is a pioneer, change-maker, and a true inspiration for the City of Los Angeles and the State of California. 

Ms. Watson spent her entire career fighting for equality and equity for women and people of color, creating an incredible life and legacy of public service.

On behalf of the 8th Council District, happy birthday, Ms. Watson!

Today, we pay tribute to the rich cultures, traditions, heritages, and history of Native Americans while acknowledging their significant contributions.

In 2009, President Barack Obama signed the "Native American Heritage Day Resolution," officially designating the Friday after Thanksgiving as "Native American Heritage Day."

At the core of today's celebration is the recognition of the strength and resilience of Native Americans. We encourage people from all walks of life to honor indigenous cultures appropriately through ceremonies and activities.

The United States is home to over 500 distinct Native American tribes, each with their own unique languages, traditions, and customs. California, home to approximately 300,000 Native Americans, stands out as one of the most culturally diverse regions in native North America. Notably, Los Angeles, rooted in the Gabrielino-Tongva peoples, boasts the largest indigenous population of any U.S. city.

Join us in celebrating the strength and resiliency of Native Americans today and every day.

Today, we made a big step forward in digital equity. Stemming from the work of Digital Equity LA, a coalition of over 45 organizations in LA fighting against the digital divide and digital redlining, I introduced a motion to go after discriminatory pricing from broadband providers.

From @calfund’s report, we’ve seen that people in South LA are charged significantly more than folks in wealthier neighborhoods such as Mar Vista. Not only are they charged more for internet, but they are paying more for slower connections.

Thank you to my colleagues, Council President Krekorian, Councilmember Blumenfield, Councilmember Raman, and Councilmember Eunisses, for supporting this motion. Let’s close the digital divide!
